  "prompt": "What is the difference between indicated horsepower and brake horsepower?",
  "response": "Here's a breakdown of the difference between indicated horsepower and brake horsepower:\n\nIndicated Horsepower (IHP):\n- Calculated from the pressure inside the engine cylinder during the combustion process\n- Represents the total power generated by the combustion of fuel\n- Theoretical power produced by the engine before accounting for mechanical losses\n- Determined by measuring the pressure inside the cylinder during the engine cycle\n- Does not account for friction, mechanical resistance, or power lost in the engine\n\nBrake Horsepower (BHP):\n- Measured at the engine's crankshaft using a dynamometer\n- Represents the actual usable power delivered by the engine\n- Accounts for mechanical losses like friction, heat, and internal engine resistance\n- Reflects the power available to drive the vehicle or machinery\n- Typically lower than indicated horsepower due to mechanical inefficiencies\n- More practical and realistic measurement of engine performance\n\nKey Difference:\nBrake horsepower is the actual usable power output, while indicated horsepower represents the theoretical total power generated by the combustion process before mechanical losses are subtracted.",
